The basic information about Flutter on the personal computer is attached below.

When I execute the flutter doctor -v command, it tells me that my local Flutter environment is fine.

Could you please tell me how to solve this problem, thank you.

I personally tried to use Google search, but I have not found an effective solution. Looking forward to your reply, thank you.

Hi @HLQ-Struggle 
This is probably due to insufficient disk permission 
Can you please make sure you've **Full Disk Access** for Android Studio enabled in Security & Privacy?
Can you try a creating project using terminal with `flutter create demo` and let us know if it works?
Thank you

Hello, thanks for your reply, here I explain the operation.

First of all, I was confirming that the local Flutter environment is normal, and also updated to the official version of Flutter, and then created the Flutter project through Android Studio, but found that I have been stuck in Create Flutter Project ... here. By looking at the macOS process, there are multiple darts.

Then began to try to create the Flutter project through the flutter create command, and found that it can be created normally.

I want to ask, what factors might affect Android Studio to create Flutter? I confirm that my operating environment is consistent several times.

Finally, I confirm that macOS has been given the highest permissions for Android Studio, because I am an Android developer.

Thank you for your reply ~

Hi @HLQ-Struggle 
Did you setup Configuring Flutter china to use a mirror site](https://flutter.dev/community/china#configuring-flutter-to-use-a-mirror-site) ?

Thank you

@VladyslavBondarenko The Flutter project can be created normally through the command line.

We're sorry you're having this difficulty.

We've seen problems due to not having configured an http proxy. Could that be it?
https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/settings-http-proxy.html

Can you create a project if you set the checkbox labeled "Create project offline"?

The log file might have some clues. The menu `Help > Show log in Finder` will get you to it. Scan that after trying to create a project and see if the latest entries can help. If you're not sure, append the latest (not the whole big thing) here.

Having multiple Dart processes is not unusual. However, rebooting to clean up everything probably wouldn't hurt.
